Environment-climate : for a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels as well as in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
This time, however, it is about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's engagement on these issues is not new: we have had a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's largest CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: levels of 1990).
But these measures, despite their importance, are not sufficient to address the challenges facing today's world.
Rising temperatures could lead to the total disappearance of Arctic sea ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases increases as air pollution worsens.
We have reasons to remain optimistic nonetheless.
Look at these people, growing in numbers day by day, ready to act to challenge their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families descending the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Businesses are also getting involved, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the politicians and policymakers, at both national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let Europe be our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three main fronts.
First, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no choice: net carbon dioxide emissions from the EU must reach zero by mid-century.
Together, we can massively invest in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings and renewable energies, as well as key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, next-generation solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transport, as well as commercial maritime and air transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent of electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a true circular economy with minimal waste.
Every year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are converted into energy or products within the Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require focusing on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let us get to work right away, by launching, for example, a European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household and electronic appliances, and eliminating plastics from our supply chains.
Third, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, populations of wild species have decreased by around 60% worldwide since 1970.
The UN Conference on Biodiversity, which will take place in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on the revision of our standards and the modernization of the Common Agricultural Policy to support this green transition.
But these enormous tasks that lie ahead, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is always the same – and most vulnerable – ones who bear the costs.
All measures envisaged must therefore be designed first and foremost to minimize social costs.
And at the same time, we must work with our partners today for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because it is useless to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three areas could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the new EU political cycle.
For we are in an acute state of ecological debt, and it would be only fair that the Stability and Growth Pact, which applies to the public finances of member states, find an equivalent for green objectives!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action in all fields: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not shy away from using its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of eco-design legislation and the "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in annual investments to meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement.
This is a feasible goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral provider of climate-focused funds.
And the new EU budget and its investment plan, leveraging private sector investments, could further strengthen the Union’s power to act.
The financial sector must play a fundamental role: through climate-related financial disclosures, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as Norway’s sovereign wealth fund and BlackRock, to adopt a longer-term perspective and avoid what the Governor of the Bank of England, Mark Carney, called the "horizon effect."
Finally, although some member states may see this as a risky project, we must hold a debate on taxation, but also on fossil fuel subsidies. In short, on integrating sustainability into public spending.
Beyond these initiatives, projects, the key lies in the method. For the "Green New Deal" to succeed, we must define ambitious goals and short- and long-term 'missions' that resonate socially.
With member states and the European Parliament, we must determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as with our regions, cities, businesses, unions, and civil society.
Tout cela ne peut pas être fait du jour au lendemain.
Mais nous ne pouvons plus fermer les yeux et retenir notre respiration pour échapper à la réalité de notre environnement.
Il est déjà très tard pour lancer un « Green New Deal » européen. Mais il n’est pas trop tard.
Ne ratons pas cette nouvelle opportunité !
